            "@type": "dctypes:Text",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><em><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">DC.XIX-XX.R5</span></em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The Beef &amp; the Cocoa<br /><br /></span></strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-9d7f5481-7fff-ac1e-b6cb-1112d86943a6\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Uriah and Littimer&rsquo;s complaints about the beef and cocoa, respectively, are one of the most explicit correspondences in Dickens&rsquo;s fictionalized account of the &ldquo;Separate System&rdquo; and the realities of Pentonville as described in &ldquo;Pet Prisoners&rdquo; (see </span><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"><em>DC.XIX-XX.L2</em> </span><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">above). In his article, Dickens criticized the fact that each prisoner received twenty-eight ounces of meat for every eighteen received by workers at St. Pancras (98). Furthermore, the article comments that prisoners received &ldquo;five pints and a quarter of liquid cocoa weekly&rdquo; while those at the workhouse got none. </span></span></p>",
            "format": "text/html"
        }
